    "summary": "Legalism (Fajia, c. 400–221 BC) was a school of Chinese political philosophy within the [[event:1112|Hundred Schools of Thought]] that argued for strict, impersonal law administered by a powerful state as the only reliable basis for social order — a doctrine that, when adopted by the Qin state, enabled the unification of China but also produced its first totalitarian regime.\n\nThe key Legalist thinkers — Shang Yang, Han Fei, and Li Si — rejected the Confucian reliance on moral cultivation and virtue. Instead they argued that human nature was fundamentally self-interested, and that only clear laws with consistent rewards and punishments could channel this self-interest toward social harmony and state power. Shang Yang's reforms in the Qin state during the 4th century BC reorganized society along strictly utilitarian lines: hereditary aristocracy was abolished, peasants were rewarded for agricultural production and military merit, and harsh punishments deterred crime. These reforms gave Qin a decisive military and economic advantage over its rivals. When [[event:3141|Qin Shi Huang]] unified China, Legalist administrator Li Si implemented Legalist policies empire-wide — including the [[event:1122|Burning of Books and Burying of Scholars]] — but the dynasty's harshness contributed to its rapid collapse after only fifteen years.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legalism_(Chinese_philosophy)",
